==English==
===Etymology===
Old English [[cleopian]].

===Pronunciation===
{{IPA|/kli:p/}}

===Verb===
{{en-verb2|'''clepe'''|'''[[clepes]]'''|'''[[cleped]]''' or '''[[clept]]'''|'''[[cleped]]''', '''[[clept]]''' or '''[[yclept]]'''|'''[[cleping]]'''}}
# {{archaic}} To [[call]], [[name]].
#:'''1385''' ''For that that som men blamen ever yit,
#:''Lo, other maner folk commenden it.
#:''And as for me, for al swich variaunce,
#:''Felicitee '''clepe''' I my suffisaunce.'' — Geoffery Chaucer, ''Troilus and Criseyde'' [[s:Troilus and Criseyde/Book V|Book 5, lines 760-745]].
#:'''1593''' ''She '''clepes''' him king of graves, and grave for kings, 
#:''Imperious supreme of all mortal things.'' — Shakespeare, [[s:Venus and Adonis|Venus and Adonis]]''
#:''c.'' '''1388''' ''And on his bakke he bar and with him ledde 
#:''His olde fader, '''cleped''' Anchises, 
#:''And by the weye his wyf Creusa he lees.'' — Geoffrey Chaucer, ''The Legend of Good Women'', "The Legend of Dido",  [[s:The Legend of Good Women/The Legend of Dido|lines 943-945]].
#:'''1380s''' ''Therfor, hooli britheren, and parceneris of heuenli '''cleping''', biholde ye the apostle and the bischop of oure confessioun, Jhesu, which is trewe to hym that made hym, as also Moises in al the hous of hym.'' — Hebrews 3:1-2 [[s:Bible (Wycliffe)/Ebrews|John Wycliffe version]].
#:'''1606''' ''As hounds, and greyhounds, mongrels, spaniels, curs, 
#:''Shoughs, water-rugs, and demi-wolves are '''clept''' 
#:''All by the name of dogs — Shakespeare, ''Macbeth'', [[s:The_Tragedy_of_Macbeth#SCENE_I._Forres._The_palace.|Act 3 Scene 1]].
#:'''1922''' ''And there came against the place as they stood a young learning knight '''yclept''' Dixon.'' — James Joyce, ''Ulysses''..
#:'''2001''' ''World traveling sorcerer supreme Charles Carter, '''yclept''' Carter the Mysterious, has made a startling discovery that makes the news from Europe seem mild indeed.'' — Glen David Gold, ''Carter Beats the Devil''.

====Usage note====
The verb is archaic. '''Yclept''' is sometimes encountered, as with the above modern examples, as an excercise in archaism.